00:00:11.176 --> 00:00:11.626 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Hello.

00:00:12.516 --> 00:00:17.576 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:00:18.076 --> 00:00:19.406 A:middle
Thank you very much
for coming today,

00:00:19.406 --> 00:00:20.426 A:middle
and if you're watching later

00:00:20.426 --> 00:00:21.826 A:middle
on video thanks so
much for watching.

00:00:21.826 --> 00:00:25.206 A:middle
I'm Ken Kocienda, and
this session is called

00:00:25.206 --> 00:00:27.296 A:middle
"A Strategy for Great Work."

00:00:28.276 --> 00:00:31.746 A:middle
So I think we all
try to do great work.

00:00:31.746 --> 00:00:34.556 A:middle
I certainly always
try to do great work.

00:00:34.556 --> 00:00:36.886 A:middle
Regardless of the
results and the outcome,

00:00:36.936 --> 00:00:40.516 A:middle
certainly the effort is directed
towards doing something great.

00:00:40.516 --> 00:00:42.236 A:middle
I think that's probably
the same for all of you,

00:00:42.236 --> 00:00:44.006 A:middle
that's why you're here
at the conference today,

00:00:44.336 --> 00:00:46.196 A:middle
that's maybe why you're
watching later on video.

00:00:46.596 --> 00:00:50.216 A:middle
Now this is a subject,
that's very important to me,

00:00:50.216 --> 00:00:52.586 A:middle
I like talking about it,
I like thinking about it.

00:00:52.996 --> 00:00:56.646 A:middle
And I was last on stage
in 2012 with a talk called

00:00:56.706 --> 00:00:59.246 A:middle
"Basics + Habits,"
where I talked

00:00:59.246 --> 00:01:01.106 A:middle
about some technical concerns,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:00:59.246 --> 00:01:01.106 A:middle
about some technical concerns,

00:01:01.106 --> 00:01:03.166 A:middle
some real certain nuts-and-bolts
things about how to set

00:01:03.166 --> 00:01:05.176 A:middle
up a project and then how

00:01:05.176 --> 00:01:06.996 A:middle
to run projects once
you have them going.

00:01:06.996 --> 00:01:10.256 A:middle
But, again, this is very
tactical, sort of down

00:01:10.256 --> 00:01:14.216 A:middle
into the details, things
like code review and working

00:01:14.216 --> 00:01:17.656 A:middle
with your other people that
you might have on a team.

00:01:18.066 --> 00:01:20.636 A:middle
So today it's different.

00:01:20.636 --> 00:01:22.726 A:middle
I would like to in
this session talk

00:01:22.726 --> 00:01:26.716 A:middle
about some higher level ideas,
kind of move it up to the level

00:01:26.716 --> 00:01:29.156 A:middle
of strategy rather than tactics.

00:01:29.446 --> 00:01:34.876 A:middle
And so I went out and got a
helpful quotation from Wikipedia

00:01:34.876 --> 00:01:37.856 A:middle
to sort of think about
what the difference

00:01:37.856 --> 00:01:40.496 A:middle
between strategy and tactics is.

00:01:40.946 --> 00:01:44.866 A:middle
And so tactics are the actual
means used to gain an objective,

00:01:45.206 --> 00:01:47.706 A:middle
while strategy is the
overall campaign plan,

00:01:48.176 --> 00:01:50.856 A:middle
which may involve complex
operational patterns, activity

00:01:50.856 --> 00:01:53.386 A:middle
and decision-making that
lead to tactical execution.

00:01:53.676 --> 00:01:56.356 A:middle
Certainly, the complex
operational pattern sounds

00:01:56.356 --> 00:01:58.716 A:middle
like programming to me, right?

00:01:59.616 --> 00:02:00.416 A:middle
Definitely.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:01:59.616 --> 00:02:00.416 A:middle
Definitely.

00:02:00.416 --> 00:02:02.476 A:middle
So I think that really sort

00:02:02.476 --> 00:02:06.336 A:middle
of strategy is you're having a
big idea of what you might want

00:02:06.336 --> 00:02:09.876 A:middle
to do, and that really should
hopefully be driving what you

00:02:09.876 --> 00:02:11.946 A:middle
actually do to accomplish
the goal, right?

00:02:13.086 --> 00:02:15.636 A:middle
So today I'd like to talk
about some of these ideas,

00:02:15.636 --> 00:02:17.676 A:middle
these high level
ideas that inspire

00:02:17.676 --> 00:02:19.706 A:middle
and inform my everyday work.

00:02:20.976 --> 00:02:24.426 A:middle
But really this session
is not sort of how

00:02:24.426 --> 00:02:26.826 A:middle
to make a great project
in 21 days, right?

00:02:26.826 --> 00:02:29.786 A:middle
I mean it's not going to be,
it's never that simple, right?

00:02:29.986 --> 00:02:31.756 A:middle
Every time you see
something like that X

00:02:31.756 --> 00:02:36.056 A:middle
or 21 days it's never,
ever, ever that simple.

00:02:36.826 --> 00:02:40.276 A:middle
So it's not simple; you
kind of need a plan for kind

00:02:40.396 --> 00:02:41.846 A:middle
of attacking the problem here.

00:02:42.206 --> 00:02:46.506 A:middle
And so today how I'm going
to do that is tell you some

00:02:46.506 --> 00:02:50.016 A:middle
of my stories, projects
that I've been involved in.

00:02:50.506 --> 00:02:52.946 A:middle
But, you know, but there's
kind of like a note of caution

00:02:52.946 --> 00:02:55.586 A:middle
when you hear stories
and maybe try

00:02:55.586 --> 00:02:57.326 A:middle
to apply it to your own life.

00:02:57.326 --> 00:02:58.676 A:middle
And I have an example here.

00:02:58.676 --> 00:03:01.606 A:middle
Let's say you're in Las
Vegas and you see somebody go


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:02:58.676 --> 00:03:01.606 A:middle
Let's say you're in Las
Vegas and you see somebody go

00:03:01.606 --> 00:03:04.076 A:middle
by who is carrying
a big pile of chips

00:03:04.076 --> 00:03:07.006 A:middle
over to get them cashed in,
and you stop the person.

00:03:07.036 --> 00:03:10.116 A:middle
You say, "Wait, what did you do
to get that big pile of chips?"

00:03:10.606 --> 00:03:14.336 A:middle
And the answer comes,
"I put it all on 14."

00:03:15.846 --> 00:03:21.656 A:middle
Okay, so it's true, but not
so useful to you, right?

00:03:21.656 --> 00:03:23.706 A:middle
You go over and put
it on 14, you may

00:03:23.706 --> 00:03:26.306 A:middle
or may not get the same
result, most likely not.

00:03:26.306 --> 00:03:30.226 A:middle
So hopefully the stories
will be interesting to you,

00:03:30.476 --> 00:03:34.796 A:middle
but the real goal before, during
and after the story, right,

00:03:34.886 --> 00:03:38.446 A:middle
particularly after is to extract
out the lessons from the stories

00:03:39.536 --> 00:03:42.056 A:middle
because I think the
lessons if you take them

00:03:42.056 --> 00:03:44.926 A:middle
in the aggregate starts
stringing together some lessons.

00:03:45.736 --> 00:03:47.626 A:middle
That sort of points
toward a strategy,

00:03:47.626 --> 00:03:48.886 A:middle
it certainly does for me.

00:03:49.806 --> 00:03:55.516 A:middle
So today eight stories, 11
lessons, take all those lessons,

00:03:55.546 --> 00:03:59.646 A:middle
put them together and really
that is what informs my work.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:04:00.066 --> 00:04:02.036 A:middle
And, again, of course, I'm
always trying to do great work,

00:04:02.036 --> 00:04:04.076 A:middle
so hopefully this
will all come together

00:04:04.076 --> 00:04:05.296 A:middle
in a nice big circle at the end.

00:04:05.936 --> 00:04:09.046 A:middle
So to begin with the stories.

00:04:10.676 --> 00:04:13.936 A:middle
Number one, the story is
"Like a Crystal Ball,"

00:04:13.936 --> 00:04:19.356 A:middle
and the lesson is know a
good idea when you see it.

00:04:20.065 --> 00:04:25.206 A:middle
So I joined Apple in June of
2001, and if you think back

00:04:25.206 --> 00:04:30.606 A:middle
to that time, Mac OS X,
version 10.0, was released

00:04:31.016 --> 00:04:32.626 A:middle
about three months before.

00:04:32.626 --> 00:04:35.496 A:middle
Now that's kind of
a long time ago.

00:04:35.496 --> 00:04:37.006 A:middle
When you think about
it the browser

00:04:37.006 --> 00:04:40.446 A:middle
on the platform was
Microsoft Internet Explorer,

00:04:41.766 --> 00:04:43.326 A:middle
and that's the browser
that's shipped

00:04:43.776 --> 00:04:45.756 A:middle
with the operating
system from Apple.

00:04:46.986 --> 00:04:52.066 A:middle
Not only that, there
was no framework to load

00:04:52.246 --> 00:04:55.236 A:middle
and render web content, right?

00:04:55.236 --> 00:04:57.166 A:middle
So we just had an
app, but no framework.

00:04:57.166 --> 00:05:00.566 A:middle
So my job, along with someone
else, a fellow named Don,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:04:57.166 --> 00:05:00.566 A:middle
So my job, along with someone
else, a fellow named Don,

00:05:00.566 --> 00:05:01.646 A:middle
we joined the same day.

00:05:01.646 --> 00:05:04.506 A:middle
Our job became make
Apple a web browser

00:05:04.606 --> 00:05:06.996 A:middle
and an Objective-C
Framework, too.

00:05:07.686 --> 00:05:11.006 A:middle
Again, load and render web
content and make that available

00:05:11.006 --> 00:05:13.226 A:middle
as an API to you all,
to the developers.

00:05:13.756 --> 00:05:18.466 A:middle
So we started looking
at some options.

00:05:18.466 --> 00:05:20.466 A:middle
Well, what were the options
available at the time?

00:05:20.466 --> 00:05:23.636 A:middle
And you see sort of the
leading candidates there.

00:05:23.636 --> 00:05:28.366 A:middle
Some of these were commercial
products, kind of a buy option.

00:05:28.586 --> 00:05:31.376 A:middle
Some of them were Open
Source projects out there

00:05:31.406 --> 00:05:33.676 A:middle
in the world going on.

00:05:33.676 --> 00:05:35.716 A:middle
We could go and make perhaps,

00:05:35.716 --> 00:05:37.516 A:middle
adopt that source
code for our project.

00:05:37.516 --> 00:05:38.726 A:middle
We could also start
from scratch,

00:05:38.726 --> 00:05:42.116 A:middle
we considered it, absolutely.

00:05:42.116 --> 00:05:45.606 A:middle
So my job was to begin to do
some technical investigation

00:05:45.606 --> 00:05:49.276 A:middle
of particularly the
Open Source options.

00:05:51.046 --> 00:05:52.916 A:middle
And I downloaded Mozilla.

00:05:52.916 --> 00:05:56.626 A:middle
There's one story, I took
about a week, I remember,

00:05:56.896 --> 00:05:59.886 A:middle
to try to just get Mozilla
to build on the Mac.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:06:00.196 --> 00:06:05.506 A:middle
And I remember at one point one
of the steps in this long recipe

00:06:05.506 --> 00:06:07.956 A:middle
of steps that needed to get
done to get Mozilla to build,

00:06:08.316 --> 00:06:10.136 A:middle
I needed to rebuild the C,

00:06:10.136 --> 00:06:14.056 A:middle
metro work C library,
was one of the steps.

00:06:14.476 --> 00:06:16.226 A:middle
So this was not a
straightforward thing,

00:06:16.226 --> 00:06:18.236 A:middle
but I eventually got it
building and, you know, okay.

00:06:18.756 --> 00:06:23.696 A:middle
But this process went
on for weeks, and I went

00:06:23.696 --> 00:06:26.126 A:middle
and got these programs.

00:06:26.126 --> 00:06:28.006 A:middle
The commercial products,
you know,

00:06:28.006 --> 00:06:29.896 A:middle
what I did for that
was got them running

00:06:29.896 --> 00:06:32.676 A:middle
and started doing some
performance analysis

00:06:32.676 --> 00:06:34.966 A:middle
and say Unicode compatibility.

00:06:35.216 --> 00:06:38.616 A:middle
And so between the commercial
products, those test results,

00:06:38.616 --> 00:06:41.786 A:middle
and the Open Source projects,
some sort of reckoning

00:06:41.786 --> 00:06:45.236 A:middle
of how much source code was
there, how easy it would be

00:06:45.236 --> 00:06:46.586 A:middle
to adapt it and so forth.

00:06:46.586 --> 00:06:49.836 A:middle
Some test results, I
printed out on paper,

00:06:50.566 --> 00:06:54.116 A:middle
but I didn't have a demo.

00:06:54.266 --> 00:06:56.376 A:middle
No demo, just test results.

00:06:57.056 --> 00:06:59.996 A:middle
So right about that time we
got a new engineer on our team,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:07:00.116 --> 00:07:00.836 A:middle
a fellow named Richard.

00:07:01.746 --> 00:07:05.596 A:middle
And so I showed him, described
to him basically as I described

00:07:05.596 --> 00:07:09.066 A:middle
to you what I'd been doing,
showed him the test results.

00:07:09.066 --> 00:07:11.976 A:middle
And he said really what
have you been doing?

00:07:12.256 --> 00:07:13.876 A:middle
Six weeks and this
is all you have?

00:07:14.846 --> 00:07:16.716 A:middle
So I was like, well, yeah.

00:07:16.716 --> 00:07:18.606 A:middle
I just kind of shrugged and
said that's what I have.

00:07:18.936 --> 00:07:20.296 A:middle
So he just didn't
think very much

00:07:20.296 --> 00:07:21.796 A:middle
of that, and so he went away.

00:07:21.796 --> 00:07:24.606 A:middle
And two days later
he had a demo.

00:07:25.736 --> 00:07:27.906 A:middle
He took one of those
options, KHTML,

00:07:28.356 --> 00:07:31.636 A:middle
which is the web rendering
engine that was part

00:07:31.636 --> 00:07:35.596 A:middle
of the KDE desktop
environment for Linux.

00:07:35.756 --> 00:07:39.216 A:middle
He grabbed that source code,
got it running on a Mac,

00:07:40.226 --> 00:07:43.986 A:middle
just did whatever kind of
hacks that he needed to do

00:07:43.986 --> 00:07:48.626 A:middle
to get it running, and had
Konqueror, the KDE's browser,

00:07:48.976 --> 00:07:51.796 A:middle
running on a Mac in an X window.

00:07:53.206 --> 00:07:55.286 A:middle
This was amazing.

00:07:55.816 --> 00:07:58.336 A:middle
It was absolutely amazing.

00:07:58.336 --> 00:08:00.406 A:middle
We were just standing
there and like looking


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:07:58.336 --> 00:08:00.406 A:middle
We were just standing
there and like looking

00:08:00.956 --> 00:08:03.926 A:middle
at a browser running on
the Mac, that's like --

00:08:04.346 --> 00:08:09.376 A:middle
it was like a crystal ball,
it was absolutely amazing.

00:08:10.426 --> 00:08:12.846 A:middle
And we saw all the people who
were involved in, you know -

00:08:12.846 --> 00:08:15.036 A:middle
not only us on the project,
but then decision makers

00:08:15.036 --> 00:08:18.476 A:middle
at the company - saw that
KHTML was our future.

00:08:18.896 --> 00:08:20.926 A:middle
This was just like he'd opened

00:08:20.926 --> 00:08:23.276 A:middle
up this tunnel to,
like, the future.

00:08:23.276 --> 00:08:24.976 A:middle
It was absolutely amazing.

00:08:24.976 --> 00:08:29.896 A:middle
And so the lesson from
this experience is

00:08:29.896 --> 00:08:31.236 A:middle
to know a good idea
when you see it.

00:08:31.876 --> 00:08:36.956 A:middle
I mean really for me, I kind
of felt like a bumbling idiot.

00:08:37.226 --> 00:08:41.186 A:middle
There I was for six weeks
trying to figure out what to do

00:08:41.366 --> 00:08:44.506 A:middle
and really had nothing,
and someone new came in

00:08:44.506 --> 00:08:48.836 A:middle
and in two days he had
the future right there

00:08:49.006 --> 00:08:49.736 A:middle
that we could use.

00:08:50.946 --> 00:08:53.446 A:middle
Now sort of the sub-lesson

00:08:53.446 --> 00:08:55.256 A:middle
for this is really
what does this mean,

00:08:55.256 --> 00:08:56.366 A:middle
know a good idea
when you see it?

00:08:56.366 --> 00:08:59.346 A:middle
Is even if something like this
happens to you and you're made

00:08:59.346 --> 00:09:01.556 A:middle
to look like an idiot,
it doesn't matter.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:08:59.346 --> 00:09:01.556 A:middle
to look like an idiot,
it doesn't matter.

00:09:01.556 --> 00:09:02.346 A:middle
I didn't care.

00:09:02.936 --> 00:09:04.226 A:middle
It shouldn't matter
to you either

00:09:04.436 --> 00:09:06.696 A:middle
because there's actually
some, a couple of good things

00:09:06.896 --> 00:09:08.256 A:middle
about this experience.

00:09:08.406 --> 00:09:11.396 A:middle
Number one, I had a great new
team member who I was going

00:09:11.396 --> 00:09:14.236 A:middle
to be now involved with, who was
going to be helping me to kind

00:09:14.236 --> 00:09:19.336 A:middle
of make this project happen,
and he really proved in two days

00:09:19.336 --> 00:09:22.056 A:middle
that he was really good.

00:09:22.056 --> 00:09:24.906 A:middle
And so it was just like,
boy, the next day, well,

00:09:24.906 --> 00:09:26.406 A:middle
we kind of know what
to do, right?

00:09:26.406 --> 00:09:28.366 A:middle
We're going to start
making this future real.

00:09:29.336 --> 00:09:34.346 A:middle
And so that's kind of the
story of "Like a Crystal Ball,"

00:09:34.346 --> 00:09:36.876 A:middle
but there's a bonus
lesson here, too.

00:09:36.876 --> 00:09:39.036 A:middle
Not only know a good
idea when you see it,

00:09:39.546 --> 00:09:44.496 A:middle
but kind of this extra lesson
of make demos and prototypes.

00:09:44.946 --> 00:09:48.496 A:middle
If you're starting on
a new idea don't --

00:09:48.496 --> 00:09:52.176 A:middle
test results, that's all well
and good, but you should also

00:09:52.446 --> 00:09:56.696 A:middle
at the same time make something
that you can actually begin

00:09:56.696 --> 00:10:00.996 A:middle
to use like you want to use the
real thing that you're going


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:09:56.696 --> 00:10:00.996 A:middle
to use like you want to use the
real thing that you're going

00:10:00.996 --> 00:10:02.596 A:middle
to be making ultimately
in the future.

00:10:02.936 --> 00:10:06.866 A:middle
Get that, open up your own
tunnel to the future, right?

00:10:06.946 --> 00:10:12.076 A:middle
Get something in front of you
and working as soon as you can.

00:10:12.286 --> 00:10:14.346 A:middle
So that's "Like a Crystal
Ball": Know a good idea

00:10:14.346 --> 00:10:17.466 A:middle
when you see it, and make
demos and prototypes.

00:10:17.756 --> 00:10:27.186 A:middle
So the next story, number
two, is "The Black Obelisk,"

00:10:27.186 --> 00:10:29.556 A:middle
and the lesson is don't try to
solve every problem at once.

00:10:29.586 --> 00:10:31.896 A:middle
So continuing right
on from the end

00:10:31.896 --> 00:10:34.506 A:middle
of that last story:
KHTML, fantastic.

00:10:34.746 --> 00:10:39.086 A:middle
The more we looked at the code,
the more we were confident

00:10:39.086 --> 00:10:42.826 A:middle
that this was really
the way for us to go.

00:10:42.826 --> 00:10:44.746 A:middle
But really what do
we do now, right?

00:10:44.746 --> 00:10:46.856 A:middle
I mean what do we do, right?

00:10:47.106 --> 00:10:50.136 A:middle
And so, as you can imagine,
Open Source we go and it's part

00:10:50.136 --> 00:10:55.126 A:middle
of the KDE desktop, so we went
and we downloaded all of KDE.

00:10:55.126 --> 00:10:57.716 A:middle
But the thing is we
only wanted KHTML,

00:10:57.716 --> 00:11:02.266 A:middle
only the HTML rendering
engine, and we also wanted KJS,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:10:57.716 --> 00:11:02.266 A:middle
only the HTML rendering
engine, and we also wanted KJS,

00:11:02.266 --> 00:11:03.526 A:middle
the JavaScript engine.

00:11:04.056 --> 00:11:08.046 A:middle
So the job became to
sort of draw a line

00:11:08.046 --> 00:11:13.176 A:middle
around just the HTML part of
this whole desktop environment

00:11:14.066 --> 00:11:16.236 A:middle
so that we could just
extract that and use it.

00:11:16.236 --> 00:11:19.446 A:middle
And this turned out to be
about 100 source files.

00:11:20.346 --> 00:11:21.476 A:middle
It seems tractable.

00:11:22.096 --> 00:11:24.976 A:middle
So the next step was to bring
those files over to the Mac

00:11:25.366 --> 00:11:27.876 A:middle
and start compiling them,
one at a time, right?

00:11:28.106 --> 00:11:31.746 A:middle
Of course, it didn't compile

00:11:31.746 --> 00:11:33.256 A:middle
because we just took
this source code

00:11:33.256 --> 00:11:36.546 A:middle
that expected this whole other
desktop environment around it,

