00:33:24.676 --> 00:33:27.776 A:middle
out of auto correction, which
was much more complex, right?

00:33:27.906 --> 00:33:29.616 A:middle
Because I wanted us
to keep things simple

00:33:29.616 --> 00:33:31.216 A:middle
because I can understand simple.

00:33:31.756 --> 00:33:35.176 A:middle
All right, multithreading
is hard.

00:33:35.176 --> 00:33:37.606 A:middle
I can't even like make
an egg and breakfast

00:33:37.606 --> 00:33:38.356 A:middle
in the morning, right?

00:33:38.356 --> 00:33:40.836 A:middle
I make the egg, make
coffee, then make the egg,

00:33:40.836 --> 00:33:41.986 A:middle
keep it single threaded, right?

00:33:42.966 --> 00:33:46.016 A:middle
Because otherwise I wind
up with a messy kitchen.

00:33:46.016 --> 00:33:47.666 A:middle
OK, so keep it simple.

00:33:48.406 --> 00:33:51.976 A:middle
So here is actually
a little algorithm

00:33:52.106 --> 00:33:53.156 A:middle
for searching a dictionary.

00:33:53.386 --> 00:33:55.936 A:middle
Word list on one side,

00:33:56.656 --> 00:34:00.396 A:middle
and a little algorithm
on the other side.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:33:56.656 --> 00:34:00.396 A:middle
and a little algorithm
on the other side.

00:34:00.696 --> 00:34:03.746 A:middle
And this was actually
thought up by the same fellow

00:34:03.746 --> 00:34:05.116 A:middle
who did the KHTML demo.

00:34:05.526 --> 00:34:08.956 A:middle
And so he came up with that
good idea, and as part of some

00:34:08.956 --> 00:34:10.746 A:middle
of our other experiments,
and, boy,

00:34:11.266 --> 00:34:13.286 A:middle
I saw that good idea
and I used it.

00:34:13.476 --> 00:34:13.936 A:middle
So what do you do?

00:34:13.936 --> 00:34:17.406 A:middle
You have a list of words in a
dictionary, you memory map it,

00:34:17.406 --> 00:34:20.295 A:middle
you iterate the list once
to find the line endings,

00:34:20.525 --> 00:34:22.786 A:middle
you store those addresses
in a pointer array,

00:34:23.036 --> 00:34:25.876 A:middle
you can then binary search and
you can find whether a word is

00:34:25.876 --> 00:34:28.545 A:middle
in the dictionary
really, really fast.

00:34:29.196 --> 00:34:31.466 A:middle
Really, really fast, and so next

00:34:31.466 --> 00:34:33.596 A:middle
after that I wrote a
custom C++ string class

00:34:33.596 --> 00:34:38.076 A:middle
that could wrap any string
in that memory map area.

00:34:38.076 --> 00:34:40.626 A:middle
Each of those strings were
null terminated on the end,

00:34:40.626 --> 00:34:43.176 A:middle
so you could just kind of
go and wrap an address,

00:34:43.176 --> 00:34:46.896 A:middle
and you have a string, as long
as you're at a line start.

00:34:46.896 --> 00:34:49.005 A:middle
And so this turned out to
be really, really fast.

00:34:49.005 --> 00:34:51.766 A:middle
I could check dictionary
membership in microseconds,

00:34:52.106 --> 00:34:55.036 A:middle
even on the original
iPhone hardware.

00:34:55.286 --> 00:34:57.696 A:middle
So this was now really,
really fast.

00:34:57.696 --> 00:35:01.116 A:middle
And so what this did was
it made speculation really,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:34:57.696 --> 00:35:01.116 A:middle
And so what this did was
it made speculation really,

00:35:01.196 --> 00:35:05.666 A:middle
really cheap, and that in turn
made auto correction possible.

00:35:05.726 --> 00:35:11.796 A:middle
So I could go from this and
take all of those permutations,

00:35:11.836 --> 00:35:15.796 A:middle
even for as long a word as
you might find in a language,

00:35:16.346 --> 00:35:20.726 A:middle
and actually go and figure out
whether that word is going to be

00:35:20.726 --> 00:35:21.806 A:middle
in the dictionary or not

00:35:22.386 --> 00:35:24.336 A:middle
and whether similar
options would be as well.

00:35:24.866 --> 00:35:26.646 A:middle
And this turned out
to be so fast

00:35:26.956 --> 00:35:29.626 A:middle
that I stored no state
for the current word.

00:35:29.876 --> 00:35:31.426 A:middle
I didn't store previous results.

00:35:31.426 --> 00:35:34.426 A:middle
All I did was actually store the
string for the user's typing.

00:35:34.666 --> 00:35:38.186 A:middle
If we think back here, all
I've had stored is I T.

00:35:38.646 --> 00:35:39.416 A:middle
What have you typed?

00:35:39.576 --> 00:35:42.436 A:middle
The actual characters
that were lit up, right?

00:35:42.436 --> 00:35:43.506 A:middle
Not the neighboring ones.

00:35:43.916 --> 00:35:46.556 A:middle
But the only thing
stored was the characters

00:35:46.556 --> 00:35:47.956 A:middle
that were lit up, okay?

00:35:48.106 --> 00:35:49.466 A:middle
So only store that string.

00:35:49.706 --> 00:35:52.396 A:middle
So it's actually, I reran
the entire algorithm

00:35:52.396 --> 00:35:57.646 A:middle
on every keystroke from
scratch, which means of course

00:35:57.646 --> 00:35:58.736 A:middle
that it searched the
whole dictionary,

00:35:58.736 --> 00:36:01.986 A:middle
70,000 plus words,
on every keystroke.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:35:58.736 --> 00:36:01.986 A:middle
70,000 plus words,
on every keystroke.

00:36:03.326 --> 00:36:06.036 A:middle
Because, to me, this
was the simplest thing,

00:36:06.036 --> 00:36:07.276 A:middle
as I was thinking about it,

00:36:07.276 --> 00:36:09.576 A:middle
it was the simplest
thing which might work.

00:36:10.196 --> 00:36:12.696 A:middle
And by coming up with
sufficiently fast

00:36:13.066 --> 00:36:15.006 A:middle
implementations of this,

00:36:15.006 --> 00:36:18.056 A:middle
it turned out that the
simplest thing did work.

00:36:19.846 --> 00:36:21.926 A:middle
Simple is often speedy,

00:36:22.446 --> 00:36:26.296 A:middle
and simple was something
I could understand.

00:36:26.586 --> 00:36:28.576 A:middle
And when there are
bugs I could understand

00:36:28.576 --> 00:36:30.186 A:middle
where those bugs
might have been,

00:36:30.846 --> 00:36:35.486 A:middle
and that's every word
on every keystroke.

00:36:36.006 --> 00:36:38.646 A:middle
Choose the simplest
thing which might work.

00:36:39.346 --> 00:36:41.556 A:middle
And again if you're kind of
looking from the beginning

00:36:41.556 --> 00:36:44.766 A:middle
of a project trying to think
to the end of a project

00:36:44.766 --> 00:36:46.706 A:middle
and what you might have
when you're all done,

00:36:46.926 --> 00:36:48.246 A:middle
that's why it's termed this way,

00:36:48.246 --> 00:36:49.906 A:middle
choose the simplest
thing which might work.

00:36:50.096 --> 00:36:52.156 A:middle
If you did actually have a
crystal ball you could tell

00:36:52.156 --> 00:36:53.476 A:middle
whether maybe your
idea would work.

00:36:53.906 --> 00:36:55.626 A:middle
But I think this is,
even from the beginning,

00:36:55.626 --> 00:36:57.986 A:middle
if you kind of think
of the simplest thing

00:36:57.986 --> 00:37:00.716 A:middle
which could possibly just
give you what you need,


WEBVTT
