00:48:30.626 --> 00:48:31.686 A:middle
It was great.

00:48:31.686 --> 00:48:33.696 A:middle
It felt good to just
be like preparing

00:48:33.696 --> 00:48:36.386 A:middle
for WWDC can be really,
boy, it just always seems

00:48:36.386 --> 00:48:39.026 A:middle
like everything is down to
the wire, and this year, boy,

00:48:39.026 --> 00:48:40.416 A:middle
I was really ahead of time.

00:48:40.606 --> 00:48:42.986 A:middle
But I had one more review
for the content that I had

00:48:42.986 --> 00:48:45.476 A:middle
in my slides, just go over
the material and the content,

00:48:45.476 --> 00:48:48.946 A:middle
particularly because I'm talking
about some past Apple work.

00:48:48.946 --> 00:48:51.566 A:middle
And it turns out, yeah, that
version just got shot down.

00:48:51.796 --> 00:48:52.946 A:middle
Yeah, you can't show that.

00:48:53.556 --> 00:48:55.516 A:middle
There were just issues
that couldn't be resolved.

00:48:55.516 --> 00:48:57.916 A:middle
The details aren't
important, but there's kind

00:48:57.916 --> 00:49:01.556 A:middle
of the one big detail which is
I don't have a session anymore.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:48:57.916 --> 00:49:01.556 A:middle
of the one big detail which is
I don't have a session anymore.

00:49:03.436 --> 00:49:06.286 A:middle
Three weeks ago I had
something that was rehearsed,

00:49:06.486 --> 00:49:12.566 A:middle
and two weeks ago I didn't know
if I was going to be here today.

00:49:12.566 --> 00:49:15.336 A:middle
So I needed to rewrite.

00:49:15.386 --> 00:49:17.326 A:middle
And there were three
important lessons

00:49:17.326 --> 00:49:19.156 A:middle
that I took away from that.

00:49:19.956 --> 00:49:25.536 A:middle
And the first was during this
review session, where the person

00:49:25.996 --> 00:49:29.526 A:middle
who I was submitting my
slides for review to,

00:49:29.766 --> 00:49:31.346 A:middle
said "You can't show that."

00:49:32.656 --> 00:49:35.926 A:middle
He didn't raise his voice, it's
just like "You can't show that."

00:49:36.106 --> 00:49:41.766 A:middle
And here's why, he gave me the
reasons, but he was very calm.

00:49:43.046 --> 00:49:47.476 A:middle
And even after, I mean it was
clear, it was bad news to me,

00:49:47.896 --> 00:49:51.236 A:middle
and even he found me later
and made sure that I was okay

00:49:51.516 --> 00:49:54.776 A:middle
with this decision that was a
very hard one to share with me.

00:49:55.886 --> 00:50:00.706 A:middle
And so the lesson from this is
be kind to people, but be honest


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:49:55.886 --> 00:50:00.706 A:middle
And so the lesson from this is
be kind to people, but be honest

00:50:00.706 --> 00:50:02.046 A:middle
about the work, right?

00:50:03.056 --> 00:50:07.876 A:middle
There's no reason to like be
shouting and berating people

00:50:07.876 --> 00:50:10.276 A:middle
who are trying hard
and doing their best.

00:50:10.596 --> 00:50:13.566 A:middle
If you have ever found
me in a lab or maybe even

00:50:13.566 --> 00:50:15.086 A:middle
with what little
time we have left

00:50:15.086 --> 00:50:17.356 A:middle
in the conference before
it ends, if you find me

00:50:17.356 --> 00:50:22.236 A:middle
in a lab today, I hope I
will do my utmost to be kind

00:50:22.236 --> 00:50:25.496 A:middle
to you personally because
I'm so glad that you're here

00:50:25.496 --> 00:50:27.286 A:middle
and so glad you're
contributing to our platform.

00:50:27.976 --> 00:50:29.886 A:middle
And I want to see you
do great work, too.

00:50:29.886 --> 00:50:32.876 A:middle
But if you show me a piece of
work, I'm going to be honest

00:50:32.876 --> 00:50:34.906 A:middle
on what I think about it.

00:50:34.906 --> 00:50:36.956 A:middle
And those things just
need to be kept separate,

00:50:37.106 --> 00:50:39.906 A:middle
the personal kindness and
the honesty about the work.

00:50:40.276 --> 00:50:46.966 A:middle
And, secondly, it's kind of
like sort of this different side

00:50:46.966 --> 00:50:47.866 A:middle
of the same coin, is

00:50:47.866 --> 00:50:50.506 A:middle
that I didn't take his
feedback personally.

00:50:51.006 --> 00:50:56.986 A:middle
And the lesson is to separate
yourself from your work.

00:50:57.826 --> 00:51:03.576 A:middle
Now and I always invest a
tremendous amount of care


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:50:57.826 --> 00:51:03.576 A:middle
Now and I always invest a
tremendous amount of care

00:51:03.576 --> 00:51:08.536 A:middle
and emotion into my work, it's
my nature, I can't help it.

00:51:08.826 --> 00:51:12.716 A:middle
But after I'm done making
something and bring it

00:51:12.716 --> 00:51:15.446 A:middle
to the stage that
it's ready to demo,

00:51:15.556 --> 00:51:20.226 A:middle
I just try to then divorce
myself from that thing

00:51:20.666 --> 00:51:27.126 A:middle
that I just sweated over
making because that's not me,

00:51:27.406 --> 00:51:29.516 A:middle
that thing that I
just made, all right?

00:51:30.316 --> 00:51:34.326 A:middle
I'm ready to accept whatever
feedback anybody has and ready

00:51:34.326 --> 00:51:36.266 A:middle
to go and do the
next thing, right?

00:51:37.186 --> 00:51:40.886 A:middle
So you need to kind of divorce
yourself, when you get feedback,

00:51:41.266 --> 00:51:44.026 A:middle
people hopefully are not
giving you the feedback,

00:51:44.056 --> 00:51:46.516 A:middle
they're giving you the
feedback about the work.

00:51:47.176 --> 00:51:49.026 A:middle
So separate yourself
from the work,

00:51:49.026 --> 00:51:50.956 A:middle
regardless of how
much time and effort

00:51:51.296 --> 00:51:54.656 A:middle
and how much investment
you have in it.

00:51:55.226 --> 00:51:58.646 A:middle
And the third lesson
is, well, obviously,

00:51:58.646 --> 00:51:59.856 A:middle
I needed to get back to work.

00:51:59.856 --> 00:52:03.866 A:middle
If I wanted to have a
show, right, at all,


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:51:59.856 --> 00:52:03.866 A:middle
If I wanted to have a
show, right, at all,

00:52:03.866 --> 00:52:08.076 A:middle
I needed to figure
out how to make a set

00:52:08.076 --> 00:52:09.086 A:middle
of slides that would work.

00:52:10.046 --> 00:52:11.716 A:middle
And the lesson here is
that you're never done.

00:52:12.036 --> 00:52:17.656 A:middle
Kind of seems like some sort
of nightmare, if you think

00:52:17.656 --> 00:52:20.246 A:middle
about it one way it's that
you're never done, really?

00:52:20.636 --> 00:52:22.406 A:middle
But you think about it,
no, we're never done.

00:52:22.996 --> 00:52:28.446 A:middle
We loved the first version of
the iPhone when we shipped it,

00:52:28.926 --> 00:52:31.636 A:middle
and then we went right back
and we made version two.

00:52:31.636 --> 00:52:34.786 A:middle
And earlier this week we
showed iOS 8 and Yosemite

00:52:34.786 --> 00:52:37.046 A:middle
and a whole bunch of
other great things, right?

00:52:37.046 --> 00:52:38.246 A:middle
You are never done.

00:52:38.556 --> 00:52:41.686 A:middle
If you're committed to
working in this industry,

00:52:41.686 --> 00:52:44.296 A:middle
working in high tech,
right, you are never done.

00:52:44.296 --> 00:52:46.216 A:middle
The world keeps moving;
you've got to try

00:52:46.216 --> 00:52:47.156 A:middle
to keep moving with it.

00:52:47.416 --> 00:52:49.936 A:middle
So do the best that you
can do at any one time.

00:52:49.936 --> 00:52:52.036 A:middle
And basically you're always
shipping your latest demo,

00:52:52.036 --> 00:52:54.476 A:middle
if you think about it that way,
it's just that these demos get

00:52:54.476 --> 00:52:56.546 A:middle
to be very, very polished,
polished to the point

00:52:56.546 --> 00:52:58.546 A:middle
where you're going
to actually share it

00:52:58.546 --> 00:53:00.606 A:middle
with the rest of
the world, right?


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:52:58.546 --> 00:53:00.606 A:middle
with the rest of
the world, right?

00:53:01.706 --> 00:53:07.526 A:middle
So still on this idea, this
is a quotation that's actually

00:53:07.766 --> 00:53:10.706 A:middle
up on the wall -
very, very large.

00:53:10.706 --> 00:53:14.996 A:middle
In Cupertino, a quote from
Steve Jobs, and he said,

00:53:14.996 --> 00:53:16.906 A:middle
"If you do something and
turns out pretty good,

00:53:17.266 --> 00:53:18.916 A:middle
then you should go do
something else wonderful,

00:53:18.916 --> 00:53:22.956 A:middle
not dwell on it too long,
just figure out what's next."

00:53:23.416 --> 00:53:26.876 A:middle
And I think this is true, not
only when you do something

00:53:26.876 --> 00:53:30.276 A:middle
that turns out well, but it's
even as in the case for me,

00:53:30.276 --> 00:53:32.196 A:middle
for this session, I did
something that didn't turn

00:53:32.196 --> 00:53:35.016 A:middle
out so well, I needed to
figure out what was next.

00:53:35.986 --> 00:53:39.166 A:middle
I could give up, or I could
try again, and I tried again,

00:53:39.366 --> 00:53:40.326 A:middle
and I'm very glad that I did.

00:53:40.326 --> 00:53:41.526 A:middle
I'm very happy to be here today.

00:53:41.976 --> 00:53:46.876 A:middle
And so the kind of the big,
sort of joined up lesson

00:53:46.876 --> 00:53:51.066 A:middle
from this section is that the
stories and lessons never end.

00:53:51.066 --> 00:53:53.396 A:middle
I thought this was going to be
a session just about stories

00:53:53.396 --> 00:53:56.606 A:middle
and lessons and had no idea
that I had started a process

00:53:56.606 --> 00:53:58.156 A:middle
that would teach
me more lessons.

00:53:58.956 --> 00:54:06.276 A:middle
And so those are my
stories, and there they are.


WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:53:58.956 --> 00:54:06.276 A:middle
And so those are my
stories, and there they are.

00:54:07.376 --> 00:54:11.576 A:middle
Again, and I think, I hope,

00:54:11.676 --> 00:54:15.386 A:middle
at least that you found
them entertaining,

00:54:16.536 --> 00:54:21.716 A:middle
but really I think the important
part is these, the lessons,

00:54:21.936 --> 00:54:24.196 A:middle
that you can take out from
them, because you're never going

00:54:24.196 --> 00:54:28.966 A:middle
to find yourself in exactly
the same situations that I did.

00:54:29.896 --> 00:54:32.506 A:middle
But I think that you'll
find yourself in situations

00:54:32.506 --> 00:54:34.296 A:middle
where you can apply some

00:54:34.296 --> 00:54:37.326 A:middle
of these ideas usefully
and productively.

00:54:38.386 --> 00:54:40.656 A:middle
So, again, those are my stories.

00:54:41.306 --> 00:54:45.026 A:middle
And so now I ask you,
I urge you, to go out

00:54:45.026 --> 00:54:47.716 A:middle
and make your own stories,
tell your own stories,

00:54:48.496 --> 00:54:50.766 A:middle
extract the lessons
out from them, right?

00:54:50.966 --> 00:54:54.676 A:middle
And then figure out how you're
going to use that experience

00:54:55.136 --> 00:54:57.536 A:middle
to go and do some more
